Chicago Divvy Bicycle Sharing data

Using the information from bike riding to gain insights

Sharing bicycles in a City environment promotes a lot of good habits. It's much more environmentally friendly than car travel, it can be a social experience, and it keeps you in shape.

This dataset is a combined dataset of bicycle sharing company Divvy and a weather dataset as well, detailing the temperature and weather outside during each ride

Why do we care?¶

Gaining insights into a customer base is a big part of Data Science. Before we even begin to query the dataset, there are questions we can daydream about:

  • Can we predict how long a customer will ride?
  • If customers use this to commute to work can we find that out from consistency?
  • What stations are the most / least popular?

Being able to understand the customer base more will only help a company like Divvy be able to provide better service to them.

Let's explore the data

What can we feature-engineer using this data?











Using just the latitude and longitude start and end, we can determine what direction the customer was heading on their bike ride.

In [5]:
# Directions. Opposites are not included as these are boolean values, so they will just be the 0
df['north'] = df.latitude_start > df.latitude_end
df['east'] = df.longitude_start > df.longitude_end
df['northeast'] = df.north & df.east
df['southeast'] = ~df.north & df.east

# Converting to datetime types
df['starttime'] = pd.to_datetime(df['starttime'])
df['stoptime'] = pd.to_datetime(df['stoptime'])

We can also get the euclidean (straight line) distance by looking at the start and end co-ordinates for each bike ride

It would be possible to use Google Map's API to be able to get a more accurate distance estimate, which would be a fun thing to do in the future with this dataset, but that costs money so this is a good enough replacement for our purposes

In [6]:
import geopy.distance
def distance_calc(row):
    c1 = (row.latitude_start, row.longitude_start)
    c2 = (row.latitude_end, row.longitude_end)
    
    return(geopy.distance.geodesic(c1, c2).miles)
df['distance'] = df.apply(distance_calc, axis = 1)

We have two datetime objects within the dataframe. It's much easier to try and work with machine learning techniques on datetime columns if we just split up the data into easier values to digest, such as minutes, hours, days, months, etc.

In [7]:
### This function will take in a datetime object, explode it into these values:
### - day
### - month
### - year
### - minute
### - hour
### - second
### - microsecond
### Can drop the column afterwards if you wishs
def engineerDateTimes(colname, engineerName, data, drop = False):
# Make sure it's a datetime column
    assert data[colname].dtype == '<M8[ns]', 'column not of datetime type'
    # Locations where value exists
    truths = ~df[colname].isna()
    # Extract the date and time from column
    df_date, df_time = zip(*[(d.date(), d.time()) for d in data[truths][colname]])
# Dates
    data.loc[truths, engineerName + '_day'] = [d.day for d in df_date]
    data.loc[truths, engineerName + '_month'] = [d.month for d in df_date]
    # Year is already accounted for within 'year'
#    data.loc[truths, engineerName + '_year'] = [d.year for d in df_date]
# Times
    data.loc[truths, engineerName + '_minute'] = [d.minute for d in df_time]
    data.loc[truths, engineerName + '_hour'] = [d.hour for d in df_time]
    # All seconds are 0
#    data.loc[truths, engineerName + '_second'] = [d.second for d in df_time]
    # All the microseconds in this dataset are 00, so there's no point in making a column for them
#    data.loc[truths, engineerName + '_microsecond'] = [d.microsecond for d in df_time]
# Drop
    if (drop == True):
        return(data.drop([colname], axis = 1))
    
    return(data)
In [8]:
df = engineerDateTimes(colname ='starttime',
                  engineerName = 'start',
                  data = df)
df = engineerDateTimes(colname ='stoptime',
                  engineerName = 'stop',

Preprocessing¶

We've already done some feature enginnering to get some more information for predictions, now it's time to get ready for machine learning.

This upcoming code is going to accomplish two tasks:

- Convert all categorical variables into numerical representations with OneHotEncoding techniques
- Standardize all numerical columns into z-scores to help with processing

I would have utilized OneHotEncoding but my computer doesn't have the memory to handle it. So I stuck with just standard scalar

In [10]:
# Get a list of columns
cols = df.columns

### Takes in a default prediction column of tripduration, but can be changed
### Also takes in a default dataframe of df, but if you want to filter the data before-hand just send in a relevant slice
### num_impute is how to handle missing numerical values, default is median, if there are no missing values than
###   nothing will be affected!
### cat_impute determines how you can impute missing categorical values, check SimpleImputer documentation for more
### cat_impute_fill is what to replace the missing categorical values with if cat_impute is set to 'constant'
### data is the data that you want to preprocess
def preprocess_data(data, prediction_column,
                    num_impute = 'median', cat_impute = 'constant', cat_impute_fill = 'MISSING'):
    df_process = data.copy()
# data handling
    # The column must be assigned before dropping it
    y = df_process[prediction_column]
    df_process = df_process.drop([prediction_column], axis = 1)
# column type handling
    kinds = np.array([dt.kind for dt in df_process.dtypes])
    all_columns = df_process.columns.values
    is_cat = kinds == 'O'
    # For integer or bools
    is_num = kinds != 'O'
    # An array of all integer / bool columns
    num_cols = all_columns[is_num]
#    print(num_cols)
    # An array of all categorical columns
    cat_cols = all_columns[is_cat]   
# Machine learning pipeline preparation
 # Numeric
    # Imputation
    num_si_step = ('si', SimpleImputer(strategy = num_impute))
    # Scaling data
    num_ss_step = ('ss', StandardScaler())
    # All steps for numeric columns
    num_steps = [num_si_step, num_ss_step]
    # Create a pipeline of the steps
    num_pipe = Pipeline(num_steps)
    # Create the transformation tuple for the numeric steps
    num_transformers = [('num', num_pipe, num_cols)]
 # Categorical  
    # Same steps as above, but for categorical columns instead
#     cat_si_step = ('si', SimpleImputer(strategy = cat_impute,
#                                   fill_value = cat_impute_fill))
#     cat_ohe_step = ('ohe', preprocessing.OneHotEncoder(sparse = False,
#                                     handle_unknown = 'ignore'))
#     cat_steps = [cat_si_step, cat_ohe_step]
#     cat_pipe = Pipeline(cat_steps)
# Transformations / Pipeline
    # List of all transformations that will be put into the pipe, this also determines which operations will affect
    # what columns
    transformers = [#('cat', cat_pipe, cat_cols),
                    ('num', num_pipe, num_cols)]
    ct = ColumnTransformer(transformers = transformers)
    data_pro = ct.fit_transform(data)
    
    return(y, data_pro)

Predicting Trip Duration¶

It would be nice to be able to utilize the data about a biker / weather to be able to know how long their trip is going to last. Let's see how accurately we can predict that

In [22]:
cols_to_drop = ['trip_id', 'to_station_id', 'from_station_id', 'starttime', 'stoptime',
                'start_day', 'start_month', 'start_minute', 'start_hour', 'stop_day',
                'stop_month', 'stop_minute', 'stop_hour']
y_pro, df_pro = preprocess_data(df.drop(cols_to_drop, axis = 1),
                                prediction_column = 'tripduration')

#get train and test
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df_pro,
                                                    y_pro,
                                                    test_size = 0.30,
                                                    random_state = 0)

#fit model on training data
linReg = linear_model.LinearRegression()
linReg.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_preds = linReg.predict(X_test)

#score on test data
print("Accuracy score for the tripduration linear regression model: % 0.02f" % linReg.score(X_test, y_test))

Accuracy score for the tripduration linear regression model:  0.64

An 0.64 accuracy score isn't bad! I do use a random seed in the train_test_split, so let's see how accurate that score it, as well as seeing as strong this model is for new and upcoming data using cross-validation

                                                                    scores[scores > 0].std() * 2))

Linear model accuracy on tripduration: 0.64 (+/- 0.00)

It looks like that score was an accurate representation of the model! With a standard deviation that small, it looks like this is about as strong as a linear model can work on predicting tripduration. Let's take a look at some other models

Predicting the direction traveled by the customer¶

There are multiple different directions that I feature-engineered earlier using the data

  • north
  • east
  • northeast
  • southeast

For this example I chose to predict north but any one of the directions could be predicted

Why is this important?¶

Well, if you are able to predict what direction someone is heading, you can more easily determine what stations they are likely to head to.

In [18]:
# In order to make this a 'fair' direction prediction, we have to drop a lot of columns. This is beacuse the directions are
# feature-engineered from latitude / longitdue. We need to drop all other directions that are feature-engineered from that
# And if we know what station they end at, we already know what direction they were heading
cols_to_drop = ['trip_id', 'to_station_id', 'from_station_id', 'starttime', 'stoptime',
                'longitude_start', 'longitude_end', 'latitude_start', 'latitude_end',
                'east', 'southeast', 'northeast', 'to_station_name']
y_pro, df_pro = preprocess_data(df.drop(cols_to_drop, axis = 1),
                                prediction_column = 'north')

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df_pro,
                                                    y_pro,
                                                    test_size=0.20,
                                                    random_state = random.randint(0,100))

mult_log_reg = linear_model.LogisticRegression()
mult_log_reg.fit(X_train,y_train)
mult_log_score = mult_log_reg.score(X_test, y_test)
mult_log_predict = mult_log_reg.predict(X_test)

cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, mult_log_predict)

plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt=".3f", linewidths=.5, square = True, cmap = 'Blues_r');
plt.ylabel('Actual label');
plt.xlabel('Predicted label');
all_sample_title = 'Accuracy Score: {0}'.format(mult_log_score)
plt.title(all_sample_title, size = 15);
In [19]:

print("Logistic model accuracy on North: %0.2f (+/- %0.2f)" % (scores[scores > 0].mean(), scores[scores > 0].std() * 2))

Logistic model accuracy on North: 0.56 (+/- 0.01)

Even after dropping any columns that would be considered 'cheating', we have an alright Logistic Model for predicting whether the customer was heading North or South.
